[[Image:USFK Prostitution Warning.jpg|thumb|A United States Forces Korea poster, warning soldiers not to engage in prostitution or purchase a "bar fine", here referred to as a "night off".]]
A '''bargirl''' is a woman who is paid to entertain patrons in a [[Bar (establishment)|bar]], either individually or, in some cases, as a performer. The exact nature of the entertainment varies widely from place to place; depending on the venue this can be individual entertainment ranging from light conversation to sexual services, or more public entertainment in the form of [[go-go dancing]] or [[striptease]]. Variants on the term include "B-girl", "hostess", "juicy girl", and "guest relations officer".
Bargirls work in various types of bars throughout the world, including [[Strip club|strip clubs]] and regular bars in the U.S., [[Host and hostess clubs|hostess bars]] in East Asia, [[Go go bar|go-go bars]] and "beer bars" in Southeast Asia, [[Dance bar (India)|dance bars]] in India, and ''[[boliche (bar)|boliches]]'' in [[Argentina]].
A bargirl should not be confused with a [[bartender|barmaid]], who serves drinks in a bar but is not expected to entertain customers individually or to dance.
==Forms of entertainment provided== In the U.S., "B-girl" (an abbreviation of "bar girl") is commonly understood to mean a woman who is paid to chat with male patrons and encourage them to buy her drinks.<ref>{{cite web|title=B-girl|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?allowed_in_frame=0&search=B-girl&searchmode=none|website=Online Etymology Dictionary|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref> The B-girl is usually served watered-down or non-alcoholic drinks to minimize both the effects of the alcohol and the cost to the bar. B-girls were employed by bars in the US during the 1940s and 1950s.<ref name="sismondo">{{cite book|last1=Sismondo|first1=Christine|title=America Walks into a Bar: A Spirited History of Taverns and Saloons, Speakeasies and Grog Shops|date=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199752935|page=244|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KQJLjeJnJ8wC&pg=PA244}}</ref> In her memoirs [[Maya Angelou]] describes working as a B-girl in a San Francisco [[strip club]] in the 1950s.<ref>{{cite book|title=Singin' & Swingin' and Gettin' Merry Like Christmas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U7GzuWnnqA4C|author=Maya Angelou|publisher=Hachette|year=2010|isbn=9780748122387}}</ref>
In addition to entertaining customers individually, bargirls in some venues (such as strip clubs in the United States, or go-go bars in Asia) are expected to dance on stage, often in skimpy costumes such as [[bikini]]s, semi-nude, or nude.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}
==Methods of payment== Bargirls often receive a [[commission (remuneration)|commission]] on drinks bought by their customers.<ref>{{cite book|editor-last1=Lighter|editor-first1=J.E.|title=Random House Historical Dictionary of American Slang|date=1994|isbn=978-0394544274|page=139|quote=B-girl: a woman employed by a bar, nightclub or the like, to act as a companion to male customers and to induce them to buy drinks, and usually paid a percentage of what the customers spend.}}</ref> Where applicable, they may receive a percentage of the escort fee or bar fine paid by any customer who wishes to take them out of the bar. In other cases, they may have a periodic quota of drinks or bar fines, or both.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}
== Prostitution == Some bargirls also act as [[prostitutes]], either on-site (with the bar effectively acting as a [[brothel]]) or by being hired upon payment of a [[Bargirl#Bar_fines|bar fine]]. This practice is especially common in [[Asia]]. In South Korea, "juicy bars" near the gates of [[United States military bases]] provide [[prostitutes in South Korea for the U.S. military|prostitutes for soldiers]].<ref>{{cite news|author1=Jon Rabiroff|author2=Hwang Hae-Rym|url=http://www.stripes.com/article.asp?section=104&article=64633|title='Juicy bars’ said to be havens for prostitution aimed at U.S. military|date=9 September 2009|access-date=13 November 2017|website =Stars and Stripes}}</ref>
Where bargirls act as prostitutes, patterns vary widely. Some seek to have as many customers as possible in a given day; these women generally take only "short-time" clients. Others are more selective and accept only one customer per day, taking "long-time" customers overnight or even for a few days.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}
===Bar fines=== A "bar fine" is a payment made by a customer to the operators of a bar that allows a dancer, hostess, or some other employee of that bar to leave work early, usually in order to accompany the customer outside the bar. Although it is not universal, this practice is frequently associated with venues offering [[prostitution]] to foreigners—especially in Southeast Asian countries such as [[Prostitution in Thailand|Thailand]]<ref name=stickman>{{cite web|url=http://www.stickmanbangkok.com/girls.html |title=Internet Archive copy of Stickman's guide to Naughty Nightlife in Bangkok|accessdate=18 September 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021004052612/http://www.stickmanbangkok.com/girls.html |archivedate=October 4, 2002}}</ref><ref name=pattaya>{{cite web|url=http://www.pattayanewbie.com/how.html |title=How Bars Work|work=pattayanewbie.com|accessdate=24 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=Askew>{{cite book|last=Askew|first=Marc|date= |title=Bangkok: Place, practice and representation. Chapter 9: Sex workers in Bangkok - Refashioning female identities in the global pleasure space|url=http://www.pacificdiscovery.org/credit/SEAreadings/Askew.%20Sex%20workers%20in%20Bangkok.pdf |location= |publisher=Pacificdiscovery.org|page= |isbn= |accessdate=6 Jan 2015}}</ref><ref>[[Prostitution in Thailand#Bars catering to foreigners]]</ref> and the [[Prostitution in the Philippines|Philippines]].<ref name=rockit>{{cite web|url=http://rockitreports.com/getting-laid-in-angeles-city-almost-impossible-not-to/ |title=Sex is on sale in Angeles City, Philippines|work=rockitreports.com|accessdate=24 June 2016|date=2012-12-31}}</ref>
===Working conditions=== Working conditions vary both between and within countries; even within individual countries, conditions can vary widely between venues. For example, there is significant variation among establishments in [[Thailand]]'s [[red-light district]] in [[Pattaya]]. Some bars employ relatively well-paid women who live outside the bar, while others employ lower-paid women who live at the bar.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}
===Legal issues=== In some countries prostitution is treated as a serious crime; in the [[Philippines]] it is covered by the [[Anti-Trafficking in Persons Act of 2003]].<ref>[http://www.chanrobles.com/republicactno9208.html Republic Act 9208]. ''Chan Robles Virtual Law Library''. Retrieved 26 December 2013.</ref> In [[Thailand]], and in many other countries where bar fine prostitution is common, it is technically illegal but widely tolerated.<ref name=Askew/>
The [[Uniform Code of Military Justice]] prohibits American military personnel from purchasing bar fines, which is an offense considered equal to buying the services of a prostitute.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}
=="B-girl activity" in the US== B-girl activity has declined in the U.S.<ref>{{cite news|title=B-Girls Fading Attraction in Bars Throughout U.S.|url=http://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%208/Schenectady%20NY%20Gazette/Schenectady%20NY%20Gazette%201954%20Grayscale/Schenectady%20NY%20Gazette%201954%20Grayscale%20-%209570.pdf|newspaper=Schenectady Gazette|date=1954}}</ref> (so much so that female [[Breakdancing|breakdancers]] now refer to themselves as B-girls), but it still occurs. Because prostitution is illegal in most parts of the U.S. and is restricted to licensed brothels in those parts of Nevada where it is legal, B-girls who act as prostitutes are breaking the law. The practice of accepting drinks for pay is specifically outlawed in many localities.<ref name="quinlan">{{cite news|last1=Quinlan|first1=Adriane|title=In Kenner, B-drinkers will still be illegal, but don't call them girls|url=http://www.nola.com/politics/index.ssf/2014/03/in_kenner_b-drinkers_will_stil.html|newspaper=The Times-Picayune|date=March 18, 2014}}</ref>
Bars have been raided and closed down for "B-girl activity."<ref>{{cite news|title=Peppermint Lounge's New Owner Gets OK|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/doc/365965123.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jan+28%2C+1966&author=&pub=Boston+Globe+%281960-1982%29&desc=Peppermint+Lounge%27s+New+Owner+Gets+OK|newspaper=The Boston Globe|date=January 28, 1966}}</ref> In one 1962 case, nightclub owners suspected of having ties to a Chicago [[Organized crime|crime syndicate]] were brought before the [[Senate Rackets Committee]]. The ''Boston Globe'' reported that "one of [the syndicate's] rackets, according to testimony, is the operation of cheap nightclubs which use B-girls to solicit watered-down drinks at high prices from customers, or even engage in prostitution with them."<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rogers|first1=Warren|title=Capone Heirs Defy Senate B-Girl Probe|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/doc/276189389.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jun+15%2C+1962&author=ROGERS%2C+WARREN%2C+Jr&pub=Boston+Globe+%281960-1982%29&desc=Capone+Heirs+Defy+Senate+B-Girl+Probe|newspaper=The Boston Globe|date=June 15, 1962}}</ref>
It was once common for modestly dressed B-girls to pose as secretaries who had stopped at the bar for a drink on their way home from work. The male customer, under the impression that he had found a "date" for the evening, would buy her one expensive drink after another, only to be [[wikt:jilt|jilted]] afterwards.<ref name="sismondo" />
In 2014, city officials in [[Kenner, Louisiana]], where the practice is illegal, replaced the word "B-girl" with "B-drinker" in their liquor laws to avoid gender discrimination.<ref name="quinlan" />
===In popular culture=== [[Marilyn Monroe]] was nominated for a [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe award]] for her role as a B-girl in ''[[Bus Stop (1956 film)|Bus Stop]]'' (1956). In the film, Monroe's character, Chérie, consumes four [[Long Island Iced Tea|tea-and-sodas]] before her companion catches on.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Littauer|first1=Amanda|title=The B-Girl Evil: Bureaucracy, Sexuality, and the Menace of Barroom Vice in Postwar California|journal=Journal of the History of Sexuality|date=April 2003|volume=12|issue=2|pages=171–204|url=https://www.academia.edu/7442855 |doi=10.1353/sex.2003.0087}}</ref>
B-girls are referenced in the fourth season ''[[M*A*S*H]]'' episode "Deluge".{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}
