{{good article}}
{{Use South African English|date=June 2014}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}
{{Italic title}}
'''''Boerehaat''''' is an [[Afrikaans]] word that means "[[ethnic hatred]] of [[Boer]]s",<ref name=Hope>{{cite news|last1=Hope|first1=Christopher|title=Books: Hairybacks and white kaffirs|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/books-hairybacks-and-white-kaffirs-1351381.html|accessdate=14 June 2014|work=The Independent|date=9 November 1996|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140614103034/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/books-hairybacks-and-white-kaffirs-1351381.html|archivedate=14 June 2014|deadurl=no|quote=whenever English speakers objected to living in a racial zoo designed to protect the mythical purity of Afrikaner nationalists, they were accused by their masters of giving way to Boerehaat (hatred of the Boers)}}</ref> or [[Afrikaner]]s as they became known after the [[Second Boer War]].<ref name=Kent>{{cite journal|last1=Kent|first1=Kelley S.|title=Propaganda, Public Opinion, and the Second South African Boer War|journal=Student Pulse|date=2013|volume=5|issue=10|url=http://www.studentpulse.com/articles/781/propaganda-public-opinion-and-the-second-south-african-boer-war|accessdate=19 June 2014|quote=After the war, the Boers became known to the world as 'Afrikaners'.}}</ref> The related term ''Boerehater'' ({{lang-en|"Boer-hater" or "Boer hater"}}) has been used to describe a person who hates, prejudices or criticises Boers or Afrikaners.<ref name=HAT>{{cite book|title=[[Handwoordeboek van die Afrikaanse Taal|HAT]]|date=2000|publisher=Perskor|location=Johannesburg|isbn=9780628037695|page=104|quote="Someone who hates Afrikaners and tries to harm or prejudice them"}}</ref><ref name=duPreez>{{cite book|last1=du Preez|first1=Max|title=Pale Native: Memories of a Renegade Reporter|date=2004|publisher=Zebra Press|location=Cape Town|isbn=9781868729135|page=65,143|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9zThrIM5GhIC|quote=a ''Boerehater'', someone who hated Afrikaners}}</ref>

These terms were initially applied to [[British people]] perceived as prejudiced against the Boers, in the context of political conflict between the British and the Boers in southern Africa which culminated in the British defeat of the Boers in the Second Boer War. Accusations of ''Boerehaat'' have subsequently been made by [[Afrikaner nationalism|Afrikaner nationalist]]s to exploit historical British prejudice against the Boers for political gain. They have applied the term ''Boerehater'' to anyone who criticised them or opposed their interests in the Cape Colony, including English-speaking [[white South African]]s, [[dissident]] Afrikaners and [[black people|black]] South Africans.

==Etymology and origin==
{{See also|History of South Africa#British at the Cape|Boer Wars}}
[[File:An AD MISERICORDIAM appeal - Lantern - 13 March 1880.jpg|thumb|1880 [[Editorial cartoon|political cartoon]] by [[William Howard Schröder|W. H. Schröder]] in ''[[The Lantern (Cape newspaper)|The Lantern]]'' depicting a Boer petitioning Britain for continued independence. The [[Anthropomorphism|personification]] of [[annexation]] is associated with prosperity, independence with anarchy and bankruptcy.]]
''Boerehaat'' is an [[Afrikaans]] word meaning hatred of the [[Boer]]s,<ref name=Hope/> or [[Afrikaner]]s as they became known after the [[Second Boer War]].<ref name=Kent/> The related term ''Boerehater'' ({{lang-en|"Boer-hater" or "Boer hater"}}) has been used to describe a person who hates, prejudices or criticises the Boers, or Afrikaners.<ref name=HAT/><ref name=duPreez/>

The disdain of the British people for the Boers was recorded as early as the 18th century. The Boers were portrayed to the British public in literature and [[editorial cartoon]]s as uncivilised and cruel,<ref name=Burton>{{cite book|last=Burton|first=Antoinette|chapter='States of injury': Josephine Butler on slavery, citizenship and the Boer War|editor1-last=Fletcher|editor1-first=Ian Christopher|editor2-last=Levine|editor2-first=Philippa|editor3-last=Mayhall|editor3-first=Laura E. Nym|title=Women's Suffrage in the British Empire: Citizenship, Nation and Race|date=2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135639990|page=25|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7U5hln57PtkC|quote=English images of the oppressive, uncouth Afrikaner dated back to the eighteenth century and, as Todd Lee has shown, the war in South Africa brought these images before the public in quite dramatic ways through fiction and the political cartoon, genres which caricatured the Boer male as criminal, dull-witted, and brutal.}}</ref> especially in order to obtain the support of the British public for British [[imperialism]] and the Second Boer War.<ref name=Kent/><ref name=Hanf>{{cite book|last1=Hanf|first1=Theodor|title=South Africa, the Prospects of Peaceful Change: An Empirical Enquiry into the Possibility of Democratic Conflict Regulation|date=1981|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=9780253353948|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ugTO-eg84bcC}}</ref>{{rp|34}}<ref name=Miller>{{cite book|last1=Miller|first1=Stephen M.|title=Volunteers on the Veld: Britain's Citizen-soldiers and the South African War, 1899–1902|date=2007|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|location=Norman|isbn=9780806138640|page=131|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9jZEtTfeyigC}}</ref> The English term ''Boer-hater'' was used in a political context in the British [[Cape Colony]] as early as 1889, referring to persons opposing [[Cape Dutch]] interests, the use of their language in Parliament in particular.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Dilke|first1=Charles Wentworth|authorlink=Sir Charles Dilke, 2nd Baronet|title=Problems of Greater Britain: Volume 1|date=1890|page=472|url=https://archive.org/details/problemsofgreate01dilk|accessdate=15 June 2014|publisher=Macmillan and Co.|location=London}}</ref>

===Second Boer War===
British politician [[James Bryce, 1st Viscount Bryce|James Bryce]], writing about the attitude of [[uitlander]]s (English-speaking immigrants) towards the Boer authorities in the independent [[South African Republic|Transvaal Republic]] during the [[Witwatersrand Gold Rush]] following the discovery of gold in 1886, states: "English became the general spoken tongue not only of Johannesburg, but of the mining districts generally. Hearing nothing but English spoken, seeing nothing all round them that was not far more English than Dutch, though English with a half-colonial, half-American tinge, it was natural that the bulk of the Uitlanders should deem themselves to be in a country which had become virtually English, and should see something unreasonable or even grotesque in the control of a small body of persons whom they deemed in every way their inferiors."<ref>{{cite book|last=Bryce|first=James|title=Impressions of South Africa|date=1899|publisher=Macmillan and Co., Limited|location=London|page=409|url=https://archive.org/details/impressionsofso00bryc}}</ref> British critic of imperialism [[John A. Hobson]] writes about attitudes towards senior Boer officials: "Regarding the higher officials, the opinion of all, save the blind Boer-hater, is that they are a fairly competent and fairly honest body of men."<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hobson|first1=John A.|authorlink=John A. Hobson|title=The War in South Africa: Its Causes and Effects|date=1900|publisher=James Nisbet and Co., Limited|location=London|page=76|url=https://archive.org/details/warinsouthafrica00hobsuoft|accessdate=14 June 2014}}</ref>

Animosity between the British and the Boers intensified in the run-up to the [[Second Boer War]] fought from 1899 to 1902, and continued thereafter.<ref name=Hanf/>{{rp|169–173}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Lowry|first=Donald|chapter='Making fresh Britains across the seas': Imperial authority and anti-feminism in Rhodesia|editor1-last=Fletcher|editor1-first=Ian Christopher|editor2-last=Levine|editor2-first=Philippa|editor3-last=Mayhall|editor3-first=Laura E. Nym|title=Women's Suffrage in the British Empire: Citizenship, Nation and Race|date=2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135639990|page=181|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7U5hln57PtkC}}</ref> One British volunteer soldier sent home a letter explicitly detailing the British soldiers' hatred of their Boer enemy: "The Cape Dutch and Boers are a dirty treacherous lot and as soon as the Transvaal is subdued and the beggars (those that survive) trek farther out of our way the better. We do hate them down here like poison. The rascally dirty varmints, they must be exterminated; the country swarms with them and their dirty compatriots the German Jew."<ref name=Miller/>

Approximately 27,000 Boer women and children died in British [[concentration camps]], resulting in a long-lasting legacy of bitterness towards the British and claims of [[genocide]] of Afrikaners.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Totten|first1=Samuel|last2=Bartrop|first2=Paul R.|title=Dictionary of Genocide|chapter=Concentration Camps, South African War|date=2008|publisher=Greenwood Press|location=Westport, CT|isbn=9780313346415|pages=84–85|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rgGA91skoP4C}}</ref> The British won the war, but anti-British sentiment contributed to the rise of Afrikaner nationalism and the pro-Afrikaner [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]] was the ruling party of [[South Africa]] from 1948 until 1994, the [[apartheid]] era.<ref name=Hanf/>{{rp|33–34}}<ref>{{cite book|last1=West|first1=Michael O.|title=The Rise of an African Middle Class: Colonial Zimbabwe, 1898–1965|date=2002|publisher=Indiana University Press|location=Bloomington|isbn=9780253109330|page=183|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BLREQGMgZ9AC}}</ref>

==Apartheid era==
{{See also|Apartheid#Unity among white South Africans|British diaspora in Africa#White minority rule}}
{{Quote box|width=215px|align=right|quote=The Afrikaner Nationalist is not an individualist. His whole sense of identity is bound up with conforming to his own homogeneous in-group. He tends to conform in religious worship, in unquestioning allegiance to authoritarian figures, in political ideology and in exaggerated loyalty to his in-group. Criticism of his attitudes is interpreted as an attack on the autonomy of his group (Boerehaat). He is terrified of losing his Afrikanerhood and his whiteness. Threaten these and he feels that his very self will cease to exist, and will therefore cling to them with passionate intensity.|source=Anti-apartheid activist Wendy Woods, wife of [[Donald Woods]], ''[[Daily Dispatch]]'', 1977<ref>{{cite news|last1=Woods|first1=Wendy|title=South Africa's Class and Colour Conflict|url=http://www.disa.ukzn.ac.za/webpages/DC/resep77.10/resep77.10.pdf|accessdate=14 June 2014|work=Daily Dispatch|date=1977|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140614084608/http://www.disa.ukzn.ac.za/webpages/DC/resep77.10/resep77.10.pdf|archivedate=14 June 2014 |deadurl=no}}</ref>}}
During the apartheid era, the Afrikaners dominated in number of voters, politics and civil service, while English-speaking white South Africans dominated economically.<ref name=Hanf/>{{rp|87–88,93}} The Afrikaners separated themselves from the rest of the population, both black people and English-speaking whites.<ref name=Hanf/>{{rp|33–37}} In 1971 [[Sociology|sociologist]] [[Heribert Adam]] writes "the historical friction between the English and Afrikaans-speaking populace is gradually being replaced by class contradictions within the two groups."<ref name=Feit>{{cite journal|last1=Feit|first1=Edward|title=Modernizing Racial Domination: The Dynamics of South African Politics by Heribert Adam (book review)|journal=American Journal of Sociology|date=November 1973|volume=79|issue=3|page=754|jstor=2776284}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Adam|first=Heribert|authorlink=Heribert Adam|title=Modernizing Racial Domination: South Africa's Political Dynamics|date=1971|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=9780520018235|page=179|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=63fBPXM_GG8C}}</ref> Historical friction was revived and exploited by the ruling [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]] for political gain however.<ref name=Hanf/>{{rp|173}} In 1973 Edward Feit, professor of [[political science]] at the [[University of Michigan]], writes in the ''[[American Journal of Sociology]]'': "Recent political campaigns have shown that the old bogey of ''Boerehaat'' still has its charms for an Afrikaaner majority."<ref name=Feit/><ref>{{cite web|title=Obituary: Edward E. Feit, professor emeritus of Political Science|url=https://www.umass.edu/newsoffice/article/obituary-edward-e-feit-professor-emeritus-political-science|date=3 December 2007|publisher=University of Massachusetts Amherst|accessdate=14 June 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140614073046/https://www.umass.edu/newsoffice/article/obituary-edward-e-feit-professor-emeritus-political-science|archivedate=14 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref>

The National Party, under the leadership of [[B. J. Vorster]], appealed to the emotions of Afrikaner voters by depicting English-speaking white citizens as being guilty of ''Boerehaat''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Davenport|first1=T.R.H.|title=The Transfer of Power in South Africa|date=1998|publisher=David Philip Publishers|location=Cape Town|isbn=9780864864109|page=119|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7cWNQ_C_iW8C}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dit was lekker|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-42891736.html|website=Der Spiegel|date=26 June 1972|language=German|accessdate=13 June 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113144905/http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-42891736.html|archivedate=13 January 2011|deadurl=no}}</ref> The National Party and its political mouthpiece ''[[Die Burger]]'' waged a "Boerehaat campaign" during a [[by-election]] in [[Oudtshoorn]] in 1972, depicting their [[United Party (South Africa)|United Party]] opposition, once supported by the majority of English-speaking voters,<ref name=Hanf/>{{rp|117}} as ''Boerehaters'', and won.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Horrell|first1=Muriel|title=A Survey of Race Relations in South Africa|date=1974|publisher=South African Institute of Race Relations|location=Johannesburg|isbn=9780869820407|page=1,3,7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5tJI49FjBXcC}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Thompson|editor1-first=Leonard|editor2-last=Butler|editor2-first=Jeffrey|title=Change in Contemporary South Africa|last=Welsh|first=David|chapter=The Politics of White Supremacy|date=1975|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=9780520028395|page=68|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CQjOc2kSntcC}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Thompson|editor1-first=Leonard|editor2-last=Butler|editor2-first=Jeffrey|title=Change in Contemporary South Africa|last=Butler|first=Jeffrey|chapter=The Significance of Recent Changes Within the White Ruling Caste|date=1975|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=9780520028395|page=82|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CQjOc2kSntcC}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Basson|first1=Japie|chapter='Boerehaat' – Dangerous New Nat Propaganda|title=State of the Nation: As Viewed from a Front Bench in Parliament, 1969–1981|date=2008|publisher=Politika|location=Camps Bay, South Africa|isbn=9780620409070|pages=147–149|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NJQPAQAAMAAJ}}</ref> The [[National Party (South Africa)|Nationalists]] also used the term to censure members of the [[Progressive Federal Party]] opposition party formed in 1977.<ref>{{cite thesis|type=M.A.|first=Timothy Peter David|last=Hughes|title=Political liberalism in South Africa in the 1980s and the formation of the Democratic Party|publisher=University of Cape Town|year=1994|page=134}}</ref> After interviewing various South Africans including government officials during the early 1980s, American historian [[Otto Scott]] writes: "This sort of xenophobic solidarity perceived the opposition as Boer haters."<ref>{{cite book|last1=Scott|first1=Otto|authorlink=Otto Scott|title=The Other End of the Lifeboat|date=1985|publisher=Regnery Books|location=Chicago|isbn=9780895266026|page=179|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DHshAAAAMAAJ}}</ref>

White South African critics of apartheid, such as liberal politician [[Alex Boraine]] and Afrikaner anti-apartheid activist [[Beyers Naudé]], were labelled unpatriotic ''Boerehaters'' by Nationalists and the Afrikaans press in an attempt to discredit them. White dissidents were also associated with the ''[[rooi gevaar]]'' ("[[communism|communist]] threat").<ref name=duPreez/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Allen|first1=John|title=Rabble-Rouser for Peace: The Authorized Biography of Desmond Tutu|date=2006|publisher=Simon and Schuster|location=New York|isbn=9780743298667|page=363|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IIxMu_US0ssC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=A man of principle|url=http://152.111.1.87/argief/berigte/citypress/2010/05/20/CP/10/VZboraine.html|accessdate=13 June 2014|work=City Press|date=20 May 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140613132806/http://152.111.1.87/argief/berigte/citypress/2010/05/20/CP/10/VZboraine.html|archivedate=13 June 2014|deadurl=no}} (obituary of [[Frederik van Zyl Slabbert]])</ref> South African poet and writer [[Guy Butler (poet)|Guy Butler]] was called a ''Boerehater'' by Afrikaners for his promotion of English-language literature and his opposition to [[Afrikaner nationalism]] and the National Party.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Thurman|first1=Chris|title=Guy Butler: Reassessing a South African Literary Life|date=2010|publisher=University of KwaZulu-Natal Press|location=Scottsville, South Africa|isbn=9781869141837}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Crous|first1=Marius|title=Guy Butler: Reassessing a South African Literary Life (book review)|url=http://152.111.1.87/argief/berigte/dieburger/2010/10/25/SK/13/Boek1.html|accessdate=13 June 2014|work=Die Burger|date=25 October 2010|language=Afrikaans|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140613150303/http://152.111.1.87/argief/berigte/dieburger/2010/10/25/SK/13/Boek1.html|archivedate=13 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref>

English-speaking film critics were more lenient towards Afrikaans-language films lest they be accused of ''Boerehaat''. According to ''[[The Star (South Africa)|The Star]]'' film critic Robert Greig, "An apology situation developed with the English-language newspapers who tended not to slam Afrikaans films because they didn't want to be accused of ''boerehaat'' (Boer-hater)." According to film critic [[Barry Ronge]], "The cries of ''boerehaat'' come from the industry itself when they feel they are not getting 'support'."<ref>{{cite book|last1=Tomaselli|first1=Keyan|title=The Cinema of Apartheid: Race and Class in South African Film|date=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317928409|page=102|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d5xWAgAAQBAJ}}</ref>

==Post-apartheid era==
{{See also|Julius Malema#"Shoot the Boer" song|Hate speech#South Africa}}

In 1995 [[African National Congress|ANC]] politician [[Zola Skweyiya]] was accused of ''Boerehaat'' by ''Die Burger'' for disrespecting the Afrikaans official language in [[Parliament of South Africa|Parliament]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Boerehaat|url=http://152.111.1.87/argief/berigte/dieburger/1995/06/28/14/3.html|language=Afrikaans|accessdate=16 June 2014|work=Die Burger|date=28 June 1995|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140616084739/http://152.111.1.87/argief/berigte/dieburger/1995/06/28/14/3.html|archivedate=16 June 2014 |deadurl=no}}</ref> In 1998 [[Jaap Marais]], Afrikaner nationalist leader of the [[Right-wing politics|right-wing]] [[Herstigte Nasionale Party]], described the post-apartheid [[Truth and Reconciliation Commission (South Africa)|Truth and Reconciliation Commission]] as an exercise in ''Boerehaat''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Net oefening in Boerehaat, sê HNP|url=http://152.111.1.87/argief/berigte/dieburger/1998/10/30/2/13.html|language=Afrikaans|trans-title=Only exercise in Boerehaat, says HNP|accessdate=14 June 2014|work=Die Burger|date=30 October 1998|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140614091146/http://152.111.1.87/argief/berigte/dieburger/1998/10/30/2/13.html|archivedate=14 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref>

In 2011 South African politician [[Julius Malema]] was found guilty of [[hate speech]] in the [[High Court of South Africa|High Court]] in [[Johannesburg]] for repeatedly singing the [[Protest song#Anti-apartheid protest music|anti-apartheid protest song]] "Shoot the Boer" at political gatherings. Civil rights organisation [[AfriForum]] accused Malema of inciting violence against white South Africans, citing the ongoing spate of [[South African farm attacks|farm attacks]] (the literal meaning of ''Boer'' is "farmer"). Judge Colin Lamont ruled that Malema's singing of the song in a [[History of South Africa (1994–present)|post-apartheid South Africa]] was "derogatory, dehumanising and hurtful" to the Afrikaner [[minority group]]. Lamont said "People must develop new customs and rejoice in a developing society by giving up old practices which are hurtful to members who live in that society with them."<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=David|title=South African court finds ANC's Julius Malema guilty of hate speech|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/mar/15/anc-julius-malema-guilty-hate-speech|accessdate=13 June 2014|work=The Guardian|date=15 March 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140212225434/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/mar/15/anc-julius-malema-guilty-hate-speech|archivedate=12 February 2014|deadurl=no}}<!-- this article is primarily about a completely different case involving malema --></ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Laing|first1=Aislinn|title=Julius Malema found guilty of hate speech for singing 'Shoot the Boer'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/southafrica/8757630/Julius-Malema-found-guilty-of-hate-speech-for-singing-Shoot-the-Boer.html|accessdate=13 June 2014|work=The Telegraph|date=12 September 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928210448/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/southafrica/8757630/Julius-Malema-found-guilty-of-hate-speech-for-singing-Shoot-the-Boer.html|archivedate=28 September 2011|deadurl=no}}</ref>

In an incident reminiscent of the National Party's ''Boerehaat'' propaganda campaign during apartheid, ANC deputy president [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] urged disgruntled residents of the [[Limpopo]] province to vote in the [[South African general election, 2014|2014 general election]] otherwise "the Boers will come back to control us".<ref>{{cite news|title=Vote or 'Boers' will come back to power – Cyril Ramaphosa|url=http://www.citypress.co.za/politics/vote-boers-will-come-back-power-cyril-ramaphosa/|accessdate=16 June 2014|work=City Press|date=11 November 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131114012305/http://www.citypress.co.za/politics/vote-boers-will-come-back-power-cyril-ramaphosa|archivedate=14 November 2013|deadurl=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Poplak|first1=Richard|title=The Boers are back and the 2014 shape of things to come|url=http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-11-11-the-boers-are-back-and-the-2014-shape-of-things-to-come/#.U5__TpSSyyg|accessdate=17 June 2014|work=Daily Maverick|date=11 November 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113193314/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-11-11-the-boers-are-back-and-the-2014-shape-of-things-to-come/|archivedate=13 November 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Boer' comment not meant to cause offence – Cyril Ramaphosa|url=http://www.citypress.co.za/politics/boer-comment-meant-cause-offence-cyril-ramaphosa/|accessdate=17 June 2014|work=City Press|date=12 November 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113092653/http://www.citypress.co.za/politics/boer-comment-meant-cause-offence-cyril-ramaphosa/|archivedate=13 November 2013|deadurl=yes}}</ref> [[Freedom Front Plus]] leader [[Pieter Mulder]] described his remarks as "primitive scare tactics" and "racist and polarising".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moloto |first1=Moloko |title=Cyril blasted over Boer comment |url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/cyril-blasted-over-boer-comment-1.1605799#.U6AAJ5SSyyg |accessdate=17 June 2014 |work=The Star |date=12 November 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6QOVqbAA2?url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/cyril-blasted-over-boer-comment-1.1605799 |archivedate=17 June 2014 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref>

Sociologist [[Michael Neocosmos]] notes that critics of the ruling ANC can similarly be labelled as "standing outside the state-defined national consensus", with for example ''[[ad hominem]]'' accusations of [[racism]] and disloyalty replacing accusations of ''Boerehaat'' and communist sympathies which are hard to defend.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Neocosmos|first1=Michael|authorlink=Michael Neocosmos|title=Thinking the Impossible? Elements of a Critique of Political Liberalism in Southern Africa|journal=Identity, Culture and Politics|publisher=CODESRIA|date=2004|volume=5|issue=1,2|pages=207–234|url=http://www.codesria.org/IMG/pdf/neocosmos.pdf|accessdate=14 June 2014}}</ref>

