{{Other uses|Pillbox (disambiguation){{!}}Pillbox}} [[File:Moon and pillbox - geograph.org.uk - 325948 crop.jpg|thumb|350px|A [[World War II]] hexagonal pillbox – on the bank of the [[Mells River]] at [[Lullington, Somerset]], England.]]
A '''pillbox''' is a type of [[blockhouse]], or concrete dug-in guard post, normally equipped with [[embrasure|loopholes]] through which to fire weapons. It is in effect a trench firing step hardened to protect against small-arms fire and grenades and raised to improve the field of fire.
==Etymology== The origin of the term is disputed. It has been widely assumed to be a jocular reference to the perceived similarity of the fortifications to the cylindrical and hexagonal boxes in which medical pills were once sold.<ref>Hellis, John. [http://www.pillbox-study-group.org.uk/index.php/the-pillbox-study-group/why-pillbox/ "Why the name Pillbox?"] Pillbox Study Group</ref> However, it seems more likely that it originally alluded to [[pillar box]]es, with a comparison being drawn between the loophole on the pillbox and the letter-slot on the pillar box.<ref name="Oldham18">{{harvnb|Oldham|2018}}</ref>
The term is found in print in ''[[The Times]]'' on 2 August 1917, following the beginning of the [[Third Battle of Ypres]]; and in ''[[The Scotsman]]'' on 17 September 1917, following the German withdrawal onto the [[Hindenburg Line]]. Other unpublished occurrences have been found in [[War diary|war diaries]] and similar documents of about the same date; and in one instance, as "Pillar Box", as early as March 1916.<ref name="Oldham18"/>
==Description== The concrete nature of pillboxes means that they are a feature of prepared positions. Some pillboxes were designed to be prefabricated and transported to their location for assembly. During World War I, Sir [[Ernest William Moir]] produced a design for concrete machine-gun pillboxes<ref name="NA-pillbox">{{cite web|title=Papers on:- Machine-gun pill-box designed by Mr. E. W. Moir, Munitions Council member|url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C1890565|website=National Archives|accessdate=4 December 2016}}</ref> constructed from a system of interlocking precast concrete blocks, with a steel roof. Around 1500 Moir pillboxes were eventually produced (with blocks cast at [[Richborough]] in Kent) and sent to the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] in 1918.<ref name="Oldham">{{harvnb|Oldham|2011}}</ref><ref name="SEHB">{{cite web|title=Moir pillbox|url=http://sussexhistoryforum.co.uk/index.php?topic=1521.0|website=South East History Boards|accessdate=4 December 2016}}</ref>
Pillboxes are often [[Military camouflage|camouflaged]] in order to conceal their location and to maximize the element of surprise. They may be part of a trench system, form an interlocking line of defence with other pillboxes by providing covering fire to each other ([[defence in depth]]), or they may be placed to guard strategic structures such as bridges and jetties.
The French [[Maginot Line]] built between the world wars consisted of a massive [[bunker]] and tunnel complex, but as most of it was below ground little could be seen from the ground level. The exception were the concrete [[blockhouse]]s, [[gun turret]]s, pillboxes and [[cupola (military)|cupola]]s which were placed above ground to allow the garrison of the Maginot line to engage an attacking enemy.{{sfn|Schneider|Kitchen|2002|p=87}}
Between the [[Abyssinia Crisis|Abyssinian Crisis]] of 1936 and [[World War II]], the British built about 200 pillboxes on the island of [[Malta]] for defence in case of an Italian invasion.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guided tour of WWII defences|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20051205/local/guided-tour-of-wwii-defences.69984|accessdate=1 September 2014|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=2 December 2005}}</ref> Fewer than 100 pillboxes still exist, and most are found on the northeastern part of the island. A few of them have been restored and are cared for, but many others were demolished. Some pillboxes are still being destroyed nowadays as the authorities do not consider them to have any architectural or historic value,<ref>{{cite news|title=Wartime pillbox at Salina being pulled down|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2014-04-10/news/wartime-pillbox-at-salina-being-pulled-down-4577918976/|accessdate=1 September 2014|work=[[The Malta Independent]]|date=10 April 2014}}</ref> despite heritage NGOs calling to preserve them.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Leone Ganado|first1=Philip|title=WWII pillbox is not worth preserving, cultural watchdog says|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160830/local/wwii-pillbox-is-not-worth-preserving-cultural-watchdog-says.623544|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=30 August 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160830155858/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160830/local/wwii-pillbox-is-not-worth-preserving-cultural-watchdog-says.623544|archivedate=30 August 2016}}</ref>
About 28,000 [[British hardened field defences of World War II|pillboxes and other hardened field fortifications]] were constructed in England in 1940 as part of the [[British anti-invasion preparations of World War II]]. About 6,500 of these structures still survive.{{sfn|CBA staff}}
Pillboxes for the [[Czechoslovak border fortifications]] were built before World War II in [[Czechoslovakia]] in defence against a German attack. None of these were actually used against their intended enemy during the German invasion, but some were used against the advancing Soviet armies in 1945. The [[Japan]]ese also made use of pillboxes in their fortifications of [[Battle of Iwo Jima|Iwo Jima]].
Pillboxes were hard to defeat and required artillery, anti-tank weapons or grenades to overcome.
